Dec 18 2007	A pleasant surprise	It was a pleasant surprise to have the intimate accommodations that I had at this hotel. The guest room that welcomed me upon check-in was cozy and inviting. It was a nice place to rest a little before venturing the city, and after any full day of walking and sightseeing, the room was a very comfortable destination for relaxation and sleep.I stayed for two nights in a non-smoking room on the fourth floor. It had a microfridge (microwave atop a refrigerator) that I had to plug to make it work. They were fine when I had to use them. The closet stored an iron and board and had plenty of wire hangers.The private bathroom was spacious and clean with very basic amenities (e.g. shampoo, towels) and a built-in hair dryer. I liked the varying water pressures of the shower head especially the pulsing, massage type after a long day. There was plenty of hot water but took a while before it kicked in.The room decor and furnishings were really nice. I especially liked the sturdy yet comfortable bed. There was a television set but the channel selections were very limited. Still, I was able to watch what I wanted. The windows were functional. The curtains also provided privacy. I enjoyed the cool breeze but had to close them at night when it was cold. The radiator heat was turned on at night, and was off during the day. I think it had central control because I didn't make any adjustments. I brought enough warm clothing to keep me comfortable when I needed to.There was a room telephone but was disconnected which I found odd. I attached the phone cord but couldn't make a call. I detached the cord as I found it and just used my own mobile phone.Check-in window service was on the second floor. I buzzed to be let in for the first time and was subsequently given my room key and front door key after registration. Breakfast was available (coffee, hot water, pastries, packaged instant oatmeal, tea bags) across the service window, set on a table where guests can take them to their room. They were adequate to start the morning. The scheduled breakfast was 7 am - 10 am. When I went downstairs one morning at a little past 7 am, nothing was set. An hour and a half or so later when I checked again, there was a full display case of mini pastries, packaged instant oatmeal, pot of coffee and hot water. The breakfast availability was a nice touch, especially if you're there early enough to get some and not be left with just crumbs! :-)I liked the hotel's quiet location on Sutter, between Leavenworth and Hyde. I arrived from the Oakland Airport to BART-Powell station and had a 15-minute walk to the hotel with my rolled luggage and backpack. Going up the street on Powell was quite hectic due to the throng of holiday/shopping crowd. I turned left on Post and followed he route which I used to take when I lodged at the Halcyon Hotel in November. I just walked up one block to Sutter from Post/Jones. That was the only rather steep ascent that I encountered. The hotel's safe location was ideal for me. It's walkable enough to downtown and other areas (Chinatown) yet also far enough from these major tourist areas to be able to enjoy quiet evenings or moments while in the room or when exploring the hotel's immediate vicinity of cafes and eateries. I found another budget hotel through an internet search but its proximity to the hustle and bustle of Union Square made me guess that the evenings could be quite too noisy and distracting. Overall, Mithila Hotel is now something that I am looking forward to staying whenever I visit San Francisco. The rates are excellent for a budget traveler like me, and I anticipate relaxing in its intimate and inviting guest room once again.	
